5. TECHNICAL EXPLANATION: HOW LINUX MANAGES FILE I/O
----------------------------------------------------------------------
The Linux operating system tracks and routes file I/O operations via 
a three-layer structural abstraction mechanism:

1. Process File Descriptor Table: A local index table unique to each 
   individual PID. It associates simple integers (0, 1, 2, 4...) to 
   wider pointers in the global system workspace.
2. System-Wide Open File Table: Keeps a running tally of every active 
   file pointer across the whole OS. It maintains current seek offsets, 
   append positions, and file access modes (read-only, write-only).
3. Inode Table: Maps directly to the underlying raw storage blocks 
   on disk, handling the actual metadata, permissions, and file boundaries.

When an application writes a log entry, it issues a write system call 
targeting a specific descriptor integer. The virtual file system (VFS) 
intercepts this integer, maps it down through the file table to the disk 
inode structure, and securely pushes the data array onto the filesystem blocks.
